WEBVTT

00:01.538 --> 00:03.240
Hello family, Tyler here.

00:03.300 --> 00:13.695
I wanted to take a moment to invite you to Bridgetown's 8th Annual Holy Spirit Conference, January 23rd and 24th at Portland's, Colorado.

00:14.376 --> 00:18.622
The theme of this year's conference is going to be the healing after the healing.

00:19.143 --> 00:27.154
We'll be exploring how the miraculous work of the Holy Spirit is often just the first step to the deeper, slower soul level healing.

00:27.682 --> 00:36.015
Like the man-born blind in John 9, each part of us God heals only exposes a deeper part of us awaiting healing from the same God.

00:36.376 --> 00:39.722
And the deepest healing is often the slowest kind.

00:40.563 --> 00:48.556
We're so excited to be joined by contributors like Ruth Haley Barton, Kurt Thompson, Ken Shigamatsu, and Brooke Ligertwood.

00:49.017 --> 00:52.602
Tickets are available now at bridgetown.church.com.

00:52.843 --> 00:54.866
I hope you can join us.

01:05.826 --> 01:13.718
Matthew 5 verse 48, be perfect therefore, as your heavenly Father is perfect.

01:14.760 --> 01:15.762
This is the word of the Lord.

01:16.463 --> 01:17.424
Thanks be to God.

01:26.499 --> 01:28.722
My, my friends, Zach,

01:29.762 --> 01:39.314
I told the story about losing his patience on his eight-year-old daughter because she was taking so long to put on her shoes.

01:40.255 --> 01:43.880
Parents of children under 10, can I get a witness on this experience?

01:45.782 --> 01:48.766
Why does it take like seven to ten reminders?

01:48.906 --> 01:55.234
Why is shoes for a toddler like the equivalent of putting together an IKEA dresser for an adult?

01:56.796 --> 01:58.578
How do we break through?

01:59.458 --> 02:01.281
Anyway, as you can see, I've been there.

02:02.122 --> 02:08.692
So Zach loses his patience on his daughter, Eden, and then raises his voice in this outsized reaction.

02:08.752 --> 02:11.616
But he's also a good father and a follower of Jesus.

02:11.656 --> 02:14.801
And so he quickly goes to her and says, Eden, I'm so sorry.

02:14.861 --> 02:18.246
That's not how a daddy should speak to his daughter.

02:18.366 --> 02:19.628
Will you please forgive me?

02:20.289 --> 02:21.631
And she doesn't say anything back.

02:22.793 --> 02:25.237
Just walks back inside the house, sort of concerning.

02:26.779 --> 02:28.882
So he follows her inside and she says,

02:29.410 --> 02:30.291
Why don't you sit down?

02:33.276 --> 02:34.377
Okay, ma'am.

02:35.299 --> 02:39.064
And has a seat and she says verbatim.

02:40.106 --> 02:41.087
Daddy, it's okay.

02:41.969 --> 02:44.132
Let's just try to do a little better next time.

02:45.874 --> 02:48.398
And look a little bit more like Jesus by bedtime.

02:50.561 --> 02:58.453
And that, I think, is the best definition of spiritual formation I've ever heard.

02:58.473 --> 02:59.154
It's okay.

02:59.970 --> 03:01.152
Don't beat yourself up.

03:01.252 --> 03:02.174
Don't overthink it.

03:02.194 --> 03:03.496
Don't be so hard on yourself.

03:03.536 --> 03:21.244
Just try to be a little bit more like Jesus by bedtime because if you stack up those kind of days, like two steps forward, one step back, imperfect but earnest, fumbling and stumbling days with this one great aim to be a little bit more like Jesus by the time I lay my head down tonight.

03:21.725 --> 03:27.314
If you stack up those kind of days over the next year or the next decade,

03:28.738 --> 03:34.244
or the rest of your lifetime, then you're gonna end up a whole lot more like Jesus.

03:36.206 --> 03:40.150
Be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect, Jesus said.

03:40.590 --> 03:42.612
Slip that into the Sermon on the Mount.

03:42.932 --> 03:51.461
So Jesus calls us to holiness, to a life that is in this world, but also entirely unrecognizable by this world because it belongs to another.

03:51.981 --> 03:56.466
Jesus calls us to perfection, but Jesus is not a perfectionist.

03:56.962 --> 04:00.728
That's very obvious from the company that he keeps and the way that he lives.

04:00.809 --> 04:09.784
Spiritual formation then is not perfect order, perfect habits and perfect relationships, all of it leading to perfect flawless days.

04:10.225 --> 04:13.751
Spiritual formation is something more like, it's okay.

04:14.893 --> 04:20.242
Just try to do a little bit better next time and look a little bit more like Jesus by bedtime.

04:21.506 --> 04:25.090
In Portland as it is in heaven, that is the title of our current teaching series.

04:25.150 --> 04:26.251
It's the vision of our church.

04:26.431 --> 04:32.758
And it is the ancient vision that Jesus gave to every last one of his apprentices just applied to this time and place.

04:33.218 --> 04:37.743
And today we're landing the plane on this year's vision series with counter formation.

04:38.364 --> 04:47.954
How we're deformed by the time and place we live in and what it means for us to swim against the cultural current toward life to the full.

04:48.066 --> 04:57.063
If we're going to talk about swimming against the current, the first thing we've got to do is recognize that there is in fact a current pulling us somewhere right now.

04:57.584 --> 05:03.154
And that means confronting our cultural obsession with control.

05:04.418 --> 05:12.850
According to the National Institute of Health, anxiety has been climbing among both men and women in the West for three generations now.

05:13.250 --> 05:24.626
But it spiked in 2011 when rates of moderate to severe anxiety in America rose in just five years from 18% to 34% of college age young adults.

05:24.994 --> 05:28.160
This research was very widespread and quite well documented.

05:28.220 --> 05:39.701
It's led to plenty of opinions and a whole lot of books, all of which center on the introduction of the smartphone and the associated stimulation and distraction common to the human psyche.

05:40.343 --> 05:45.893
And so the thoughtful Christian response to all of this for those well versed in the way of Jesus was very obvious.

05:46.514 --> 05:48.658
Slow down and simplify.

05:49.122 --> 06:00.795
That's when practices like solitude and Sabbath were dusted off from the ancients and recovered in the modern church and popularized in churches like, well, this one.

06:02.276 --> 06:13.228
And the diagnosis was correct and the need for slowing down and simplifying essential and practices like solitude and Sabbath are irreplaceable at any moment in history, but especially this one.

06:13.548 --> 06:18.834
But that also leaves us with this puzzling question that we were very rudely confronted by

06:18.914 --> 06:27.042
through a horrendous interruption with the dawn of 2020 came the COVID-19 pandemic.

06:27.062 --> 06:42.397
And all of a sudden, you and I worked from home, if at all, and we stopped eating out, stopped traveling, stopped making plans and appointments, stopped going to the gym, the cafe, the salon, even the park for a lot of us, sorry to remind you.

06:43.958 --> 06:48.082
And as the months ticked by in 2020, people slowed down.

06:48.674 --> 06:49.556
and simplified.

06:50.438 --> 07:02.585
People worked less, did less, bought less, the whole world started practicing Sabbath and solitude in some sense and became a lot more anxious.

07:04.269 --> 07:04.629
Why?

07:04.670 --> 07:08.498
Because the pandemic exposed.

07:08.930 --> 07:22.090
that well-meaning disciples of Jesus could practice solitude and Sabbath, could simplify their possessions and slow down their pace, all while being pulled peacefully down the raging river called control.

07:23.191 --> 07:27.698
The pandemic exposed how little control we actually have over our lives.

07:28.034 --> 07:35.988
In the blink of an eye, we went from gallivanting around the globe on jets and tracking stocks for savvy financial investments, too.

07:36.448 --> 07:45.263
I can't plan next spring's vacation, next year's fiscal goals, next year's strategic initiatives, next season's games, or next semester's class schedule.

07:45.284 --> 07:53.778
I have no control over my future, and I've gotten used to a culturally assumed illusion of control.

07:54.338 --> 08:19.410
And so in the wake of that very rude and unwelcome interruption, politicians started making predictions about the virus's severity and the proper response to it, pundits started making predictions about when life would return to normal or what a new normal would look like on the other side of this, and pastors started talking a whole lot about divine judgment, divine healing, or divine redemption.

08:19.874 --> 08:27.433
Either God is judging the earth, or God is raging against this disease, or God is purging and purifying His church.

08:28.035 --> 08:29.158
What are all of those?

08:30.421 --> 08:36.978
Their attempts to name the narrative, to predict the future, to regain some sense of control.

08:37.090 --> 08:40.855
I've lost the plot of the story I thought I was living in.

08:40.895 --> 08:42.738
So now I'm reaching for the pen.

08:43.058 --> 08:44.640
I'm trying to rename the narrative.

08:44.680 --> 08:48.465
I'm grasping for the comfort of knowing where this story is going.

08:48.505 --> 08:50.868
I'm grasping for control.

08:52.050 --> 08:58.499
The Oxford English Dictionary defines control as the power to influence or direct people's behavior or the course of events.

08:59.300 --> 09:07.090
The American Psychological Association defines it authority, power, or influence over events, behavior, situations, or people.

09:07.618 --> 09:13.709
These definitions are both helpful, but they're still incomplete because control is also a feeling.

09:13.769 --> 09:20.642
It's the word that we use to describe our sense of felt empowerment or lack thereof.

09:21.504 --> 09:29.138
Journalist Jennifer Dukes Lee defines control as the belief, I'm safer and more secure if I'm in charge.

09:30.420 --> 09:31.442
Is that not what

09:31.810 --> 09:45.058
Every politician, pundit, and pastor was doing in the months of 2020, the ticked by, just reaching for and assuring others of safety by reclaiming some sense of being in charge.

09:46.581 --> 09:48.084
And look, that shouldn't surprise us.

09:48.144 --> 09:50.770
Control is the most ancient of deceptions.

09:51.490 --> 10:00.403
All the way back in Eden, what unwound biblical paradise in the eternal life that God made us to live in, what lied to the serpent weave?

10:00.723 --> 10:03.808
Does anyone remember the deception whispered in Eve's ear?

10:06.432 --> 10:08.655
You will be like God.

10:10.317 --> 10:13.522
And that's when a thought entered human consciousness for the first time.

10:13.622 --> 10:19.250
Wait a minute, maybe I'm safer and more secure if I'm in charge.

10:20.130 --> 10:23.074
That thought, well, let's just call it, what is that deception?

10:23.154 --> 10:30.184
Might have occurred it to Eve first, but we've all followed suit every last one of us grasping for the forbidden fruit named control.

10:31.005 --> 10:45.906
And those living in the affluent corners of the modern world, that's all of us, are being discipled, apprenticed in the way of control like no one else to ever grace this deceived world.

10:46.306 --> 10:50.671
When you order a product online, it arrives in two days at the slowest.

10:51.352 --> 10:54.737
When you want to watch a movie, you stream it on demand.

10:55.137 --> 10:59.102
When you want to know what the weather is going to be like next Wednesday, you click on an app.

10:59.142 --> 11:05.190
When you want to reduce signs of aging, you buy creams or have surgery or sit in red light therapy saunas.

11:05.510 --> 11:10.717
When you don't like the way the school system's going or the changes in the neighborhood, you just change your zip code.

11:11.017 --> 11:15.122
When you want macaroni, you don't plant seeds and harvest grain.

11:15.266 --> 11:20.833
You go to the store and you select from 10 brands that are set to your precise specifications.

11:21.454 --> 11:34.652
Oh, did you want gluten-free, nut-free, GMO-free, keto-friendly, organic, wheat-based, sprouted, dairy-free, chickpea, lentil, egg, almond, wild rice, or plant-based noodles for your toddler's dinner tonight?

11:36.914 --> 11:38.817
Are you guys out of the pistachio noodles?

11:39.278 --> 11:42.642
Oh, yeah, we discontinued those.

11:43.138 --> 11:49.447
When you want to track your fitness, or your diet, or your sleep, or your steps, you click a button on your phone.

11:49.948 --> 11:52.913
Everything is performance, improvement, and taking charge.

11:52.973 --> 11:54.415
Everything is control.

11:54.936 --> 12:01.846
And it's leading some of us to endless self-improvement, others to endless self-consciousness, and plenty to endless self-paralysis.

12:02.788 --> 12:09.918
Sharon Hottie Miller in her book, The Cost of Control, says, we used to call people who promise certainty about the future of cult.

12:11.040 --> 12:12.402
Now it's just our culture.

12:13.346 --> 12:18.374
Control, that's the current of these waters you've been swimming in, friends.

12:19.015 --> 12:20.958
Did you know that they were pulling you along?

12:23.081 --> 12:24.002
Taking you somewhere?

12:26.466 --> 12:39.346
Is it somewhere you want to go, somewhere leading to joy, to life, or to anxiety, to death?

12:41.794 --> 12:47.061
So what happens when spiritual formation cooperates with control rather than confronts it?

12:48.042 --> 12:57.234
Well, in the waning days of his life, just before his passing, the Christian philosopher Dallas Willard was asked, what fear he held for the future of spiritual formation in the Western church?

12:57.574 --> 12:58.715
And this was his response.

12:59.336 --> 13:02.640
The spiritual formation movement will degenerate into technique.

13:03.502 --> 13:07.026
It will focus on practices, not on the soul.

13:07.554 --> 13:12.461
There is very real danger in accepting Jesus' truth while rejecting Jesus' way.

13:12.501 --> 13:14.343
That's what we talked about last week.

13:14.363 --> 13:22.674
There is equal danger, though, in obsessing so much about the narrow way of Jesus that I diminish salvation and life into a technique.

13:23.195 --> 13:28.562
Assuming these practices, if perfected, will lead me to perfection.

13:28.706 --> 13:38.219
channeling control into the way of Jesus, pairing the serpent's deception with God's redemption, that doesn't take me to life.

13:39.280 --> 13:46.570
The French monastic author, Jacques Philippe, writes, there is a widespread but mistaken idea that holiness is the work of human beings.

13:47.031 --> 13:53.740
That what we need is to have a clear program of perfection set to work with courage and patience and achieve it little by little.

13:54.401 --> 13:58.386
Holiness is not the result of a program of life we set for ourselves.

13:58.818 --> 14:01.301
We do not have to become saints by our own power.

14:01.341 --> 14:03.804
We have to learn to let God make us into saints.

14:04.625 --> 14:10.432
Jesus calls us to perfection, but he does not call us to become perfectionists.

14:11.954 --> 14:15.478
And the antidote to control is consent.

14:17.040 --> 14:22.587
When Jesus prayed in Gethsemane, not what I will, but what you will, that's what he was doing.

14:23.328 --> 14:24.569
He was consenting.

14:26.191 --> 14:28.434
So what in your life at present

14:29.538 --> 14:31.542
Are you wrestling for control over?

14:34.728 --> 14:50.098
Your vocational future, like the promotion that you're angling for and positioning for, the change in the industry that you're weighing, or the front door you're scrambling to get your foot in, or maybe your relational future.

14:51.074 --> 15:01.952
Like the ring that you're so tired of waiting for him to unbox or the spouse or child that you're tired of waiting to come around or the friendship or community or sense of belonging you're desperately trying to find.

15:03.555 --> 15:17.458
Your secure future, like the bigger home, your convinced your family needs, the new school or smaller class size or different teacher, your convinced your child needs, the financial nest egg or vacation home or refinancing your convinced will make you feel safe.

15:19.074 --> 15:23.138
What are you afraid to lose that you're anxiously trying to keep?

15:24.199 --> 15:27.682
The friendship you can feel changing ever since she met him?

15:27.702 --> 15:31.806
Or the body type you can feel changing ever since you turned 40?

15:32.727 --> 15:36.130
Or the workplace you can feel changing ever since the manager reorged?

15:36.971 --> 15:42.276
What in your life at present are you wrestling for control over?

15:44.197 --> 15:49.042
And what would it mean for you to actively earnestly stop fighting

15:49.506 --> 15:55.453
Instead, practicing something like, not what I will, but what you will.

15:57.375 --> 16:18.578
What if the circumstances of your life at present, the opportunities and obligations, privileges and limitations, preferences and irritations, what if all of it is the perfect conditions through which God can shape your soul and guide you to life, if you consent to what you did not originally choose?

16:20.322 --> 16:31.295
Saint Teresa of Lesus said, I won't content myself with merely enduring, but by a free act of my will, I decide to choose what I have not chosen.

16:32.276 --> 16:36.742
Jacques Philippe calls consent the ultimate degree of maturity and spiritual freedom.

16:37.302 --> 16:44.952
Gerald May summarized the entirety of the journey of spiritual maturity as a move from willfulness to willingness.

16:45.412 --> 16:50.258
And Jesus Christ of Nazareth prayed, not what I will, but what you will.

16:50.626 --> 17:07.506
Then on the other side of that profound act of consent, Jesus took his most willful apprentice, Peter, for a walk and said, very truly, I tell you, when you were younger, you dressed yourself and went where you wanted.

17:07.846 --> 17:14.094
But when you are old, you will stretch out your hands and someone else will dress you and lead you where you do not want to go.

17:14.134 --> 17:17.618
That's on the nose, Jesus, speak for Pete.

17:18.242 --> 17:26.891
Someone else is going to wrap you in a mock robe and crown of thorns and make you carry your own cross just as you've seen them do to me.

17:27.472 --> 17:32.818
Jesus is saying one last time exactly what he's been telling his apprentices from the very beginning.

17:32.858 --> 17:38.003
The way to full life and complete joy is through a cross and a tomb.

17:40.005 --> 17:41.507
It's consent, not control.

17:41.607 --> 17:44.530
That's where practicing the way of Jesus is leading.

17:46.818 --> 17:48.100
Will you let him take you there?

17:55.010 --> 17:57.714
You will be like God, said the serpent.

17:58.455 --> 17:59.016
Control.

17:59.056 --> 18:03.983
Apart from me, you can do nothing, said the Savior.

18:04.905 --> 18:05.466
Consent.

18:06.507 --> 18:11.755
Control obsesses over changing circumstances forever planning a day that's more ideal than today.

18:12.696 --> 18:16.562
A future where my finances are finally in order or my

18:16.610 --> 18:24.121
Children are finally happy when my spouse is fulfilled or my home is roomy or when my career is more stable, when my marriage is healthier.

18:24.501 --> 18:31.792
Control always envisions a tomorrow that is better than today, a chapter in my life that is more fulfilling than the one I'm living.

18:32.192 --> 18:44.850
When I graduate or when I get promoted to management or when I get married, when I have children, when my children start school, when my children are out of the house, when my children come back into the house, when my children have children.

18:44.898 --> 18:48.401
Control is always coming, but never arrives.

18:49.523 --> 18:53.426
Consent, on the other hand, looks beneath circumstances to character.

18:53.987 --> 18:59.372
How, oh God, who works with both the good and bad in my life for my redemption?

18:59.893 --> 19:10.143
How might the imperfect circumstances of my life today be the perfect conditions through which you can mature me, heal me, and guide me to life?

19:12.605 --> 19:13.266
So then,

19:14.274 --> 19:20.262
What are the practices from the ancient way of Jesus that come back control and free me to consent?

19:20.943 --> 19:29.073
What does a life of counter formation look like in a cultural current like the one you and I are being pulled along by?

19:29.854 --> 19:33.899
It looks like generosity, hospitality, and confession.

19:35.001 --> 19:38.005
You see, generosity is the practice of consent with my possessions.

19:38.886 --> 19:42.290
Hospitality is the practice of consent with my relationships.

19:42.498 --> 19:45.462
And confession is the practice of consent with my image.

19:46.523 --> 19:47.825
A brief word on each one.

19:48.746 --> 19:49.867
First, generosity.

19:50.929 --> 19:53.432
Financial privacy is a really big deal today.

19:54.353 --> 20:02.223
Statistics show that America is among the world's least transparent countries in terms of money, like publicizing salaries and that sort of thing.

20:02.844 --> 20:07.730
So we are some of the world's wealthiest people and we don't want anybody knowing the details.

20:08.418 --> 20:12.503
The norm in our culture is you don't talk about money, you just don't.

20:12.823 --> 20:13.724
It's not polite.

20:14.225 --> 20:20.773
Financial privacy is a really big deal today and Jesus has a lot to say about money.

20:21.834 --> 20:26.319
In the Four Gospels, Jesus talks about money more than any topic except the Kingdom of God.

20:26.900 --> 20:32.146
He talks about money three times more than love and seven times more than he talks about prayer.

20:32.482 --> 20:35.466
Jesus talks about money more than heaven, hell, or eternity.

20:35.527 --> 20:41.696
The scholarly estimate is that about 25% of Jesus' teaching is about money and possessions on some level.

20:42.577 --> 21:02.066
Financial privacy is a big deal today, but Jesus has a lot to say about money, so if we're gonna talk about the way of Jesus at some point, we're gonna have to address the socially private, uncomfortable topic that Jesus addressed quite publicly and comfortably, your money, what you do with it, and much more importantly,

21:02.178 --> 21:03.640
what it's doing to you.

21:03.700 --> 21:07.145
No one can serve two masters.

21:07.726 --> 21:11.932
Either you will hate one and love the other, or you'll be devoted to one and despise the other.

21:11.992 --> 21:15.016
You cannot serve both God and money.

21:15.957 --> 21:18.881
Now, most English translations read just like that.

21:19.222 --> 21:22.747
You cannot serve both God and money, but Jesus didn't say money.

21:23.728 --> 21:24.810
He said, mammon.

21:25.571 --> 21:27.794
And that's a particularly loaded word.

21:28.354 --> 21:33.000
Mammon is an Aramaic word, but the New Testament is written in Greek.

21:33.020 --> 21:41.392
However, Mammon is one of only two Aramaic words that all the early Gospel writers universally left untranslated.

21:42.073 --> 21:43.375
Abba and Mammon.

21:43.695 --> 21:48.101
Those are the two Aramaic terms you will find on the pages of the Gospels.

21:48.542 --> 21:57.234
The loaded name that Jesus used to refer to God, Abba, a term of fatherly intimacy, and the loaded name Jesus used to refer to money.

21:57.314 --> 22:00.298
Mammon, a term of demonic power.

22:01.119 --> 22:15.439
All the way back in the first century, the Christian church was still spreading and the gospels were being written and the teachers and bishops of the early movement concluded that Mammon couldn't be translated to money because money is a neutral term for currency.

22:15.840 --> 22:20.987
And what Jesus had in mind was currency charged with demonic power.

22:22.509 --> 22:23.250
Now I know, I know.

22:23.522 --> 22:26.726
You're an enlightened Westerner who doesn't believe in that hocus pocus.

22:27.147 --> 22:27.447
Sure.

22:28.068 --> 22:29.670
Just hang in there for a second.

22:30.111 --> 22:33.255
Follow Jesus' train of thought before you pass judgment on it.

22:33.936 --> 22:38.522
Money in Jesus' imagination is more than just economic organization.

22:38.942 --> 22:44.730
It is a way that you and I attempt to become like God to borrow a line from the serpent.

22:45.110 --> 22:51.218
It's a forbidden fruit that we grasp for it and they deceived false sense of control.

22:51.938 --> 23:03.877
Andy Crouch, who writes brilliantly about this in his latest book, says, the distinctive thing that money allows us, its most seductive promise, is abundance without dependence.

23:03.897 --> 23:10.047
Mammon makes a promise to you and I that it can't keep, abundance without dependence.

23:10.067 --> 23:14.354
Now hang on a second, a way to be like God.

23:15.170 --> 23:21.242
to become my own provider and eliminate need, or even maybe eliminate the risk of ever being in need.

23:21.362 --> 23:31.563
A way I say, maybe not with my mouth, but definitely with my bank account and investment portfolio and savings and possessions, I'm safer and more secure if I'm in charge.

23:34.088 --> 23:37.234
Jesus never celebrates poverty.

23:37.986 --> 23:41.792
Basic provision is a good thing for all people.

23:41.892 --> 23:44.376
Jesus is 100% in alignment there.

23:44.717 --> 24:01.164
What Jesus is acknowledging is that Mammon, when used to insulate my need from God as my provider, when used for control of some degree or another, well, that's when Mammon is more than the number on your bank account, but a binding agreement with the serpent and the garden himself.

24:03.547 --> 24:05.170
Look, there's nothing evil about money.

24:05.890 --> 24:10.216
There is nothing inherently shameful or noble about having a lot or a little of it.

24:10.617 --> 24:19.549
But Mammon does have a unique pull toward devotion, and those who use money to try to master their world are in the end mastered by it.

24:21.391 --> 24:34.770
It's worth honestly asking, when I think about the core praxis for following Jesus, like the formation and deformation of my soul, how seriously do I take the freedom or restraint

24:34.882 --> 24:38.647
within which I want, seek, and acquire stuff.

24:40.810 --> 24:55.809
Do I think of these things which are so common and harmless according to the American way as charged with demonic power to deform my soul unparalleled by any other force masquerading in our world as neutral?

24:57.812 --> 25:02.418
Because if Jesus is your rabbi, his very direct teaching,

25:02.882 --> 25:12.053
is the acquisition of wealth and possessions is not wrong in and of itself.

25:14.515 --> 25:16.378
But it is fire you're playing with.

25:18.200 --> 25:30.514
And as my kids prove, every time we gather around the fire pit or just light a candle, fire quickly becomes destructive for those who don't respect its power.

25:32.354 --> 25:44.172
Biblically speaking, God's people are instructed all the way back in Exodus that a core distinguishing marker of his people should be tithing, the gift of 10% of everything that they accumulate to the temple.

25:44.653 --> 25:46.576
Jesus, though, doesn't teach tithing.

25:47.477 --> 25:55.329
He teaches his apprentices to practice generosity, and that means that you and I are freed from the yoke of Yahweh's 10% mandate.

25:55.690 --> 26:00.978
You are free to decide what, how, and to whom you give.

26:01.090 --> 26:11.507
But, and this is a very important but, every other ethic that Jesus teaches in the Sermon on the Mount follows a pattern, he always raises the bar rather than lowering it.

26:12.649 --> 26:15.634
Jesus says, you've heard it said don't commit murder.

26:15.714 --> 26:17.217
I say don't even call somebody a fool.

26:18.038 --> 26:19.901
He says you've heard it said don't commit adultery.

26:19.941 --> 26:21.584
I say don't even have a lustful thought.

26:22.205 --> 26:24.048
You've heard it say to love your friends.

26:24.148 --> 26:25.190
I say love your enemies.

26:25.972 --> 26:27.474
So if that's the pattern,

26:27.746 --> 26:32.771
It'd be pretty strange if Jesus went in the other direction when it comes to generosity, right?

26:33.172 --> 26:37.417
If he meant for you to start giving less than 10% of your income away.

26:38.398 --> 26:51.091
See, you and I, just by living in the greater Portland area in modern America, are statistically among the wealthiest people alive today and the wealthiest people to ever grace this planet.

26:51.992 --> 26:57.138
To put it very bluntly, if we take that into the ethics of Jesus,

26:57.250 --> 27:04.940
Tithing has never been felt less and generosity has never been more accessible.

27:07.203 --> 27:10.067
Do you give away 10% of your annual income?

27:13.191 --> 27:18.098
And look, don't be thrown off by the fact that I'm a Christian pastor asking you the question.

27:18.118 --> 27:20.021
I'm not encouraging you to practice anything.

27:20.041 --> 27:21.042
I don't practice myself.

27:21.523 --> 27:24.587
And I'm not even telling you to give to this church.

27:25.668 --> 27:26.930
I'm just asking you,

27:27.234 --> 27:34.561
Are you giving away 10% of your annual income for the sake of the kingdom of God anywhere to anyone?

27:37.444 --> 27:40.748
Can I just take a risk and nudge like one step further?

27:40.848 --> 27:44.912
And I just want to ask you a question that I ask myself a whole lot at the time.

27:47.154 --> 27:54.802
Is it easy to see a difference in the way that you relate to money in comparison to your neighbors who don't follow Jesus?

27:56.706 --> 28:07.365
I ask myself that question because it's not hard to distinguish the downward invitation of Christ from the upward pull of the American way.

28:08.968 --> 28:17.825
So if, when it comes to my money, I'm finding the way of Jesus to be quite congruent with the upward climb of American culture.

28:19.608 --> 28:20.850
What does that tell me?

28:23.394 --> 28:37.208
What if simplifying my possessions, like sharing my money and my resources, freely giving all that I've been freely given, is actually the wave consent that leads through the cross and tomb to resurrection life here and now?

28:38.790 --> 28:39.751
So there's generosity.

28:40.732 --> 28:45.336
And then there's hospitality, which is the practice of consent with my relationships.

28:45.897 --> 28:50.802
The word hospitality in biblical Greek is a compound word, philos,

28:51.138 --> 28:52.199
Phylozenian.

28:52.479 --> 28:55.643
Phylo means love, and zenos means strangers.

28:55.723 --> 29:00.308
Inaphobia is a psychological condition for the fear or hatred of strangers.

29:00.769 --> 29:03.091
Hospitality is the exact opposite of that.

29:03.532 --> 29:05.053
It is the love of the stranger.

29:05.454 --> 29:08.177
And it shows up all over the pages of the New Testament.

29:08.197 --> 29:11.220
It's in Romans, Hebrews, 1 Peter, and a whole bunch of other places.

29:11.841 --> 29:17.187
The English term hospitality actually has the same linguistic root as our word hospital.

29:18.128 --> 29:19.890
Now, a hospital is not a doctor.

29:20.354 --> 29:26.825
It's a shelter where the healer and the hurting can meet so that healing can take place.

29:27.567 --> 29:32.295
Hospitality is not to change people, but just to offer them space where change can take place.

29:33.217 --> 29:42.232
Practically speaking, then, that means hospitality is the practice of hosting both the healer and the stranger together in my presence.

29:44.116 --> 29:45.458
My wife, Kirsten,

29:46.242 --> 29:52.751
is the most hospitable person that I have ever witnessed in my life in the biblical sense.

29:53.692 --> 30:02.044
Now, don't get me wrong, she is great at baking bread and throwing dinner parties, but that's Western hospitality.

30:02.825 --> 30:13.540
What she's supernaturally gifted in is seeing, welcoming, and drawing out the other, hosting both the stranger and the healer simultaneously in her presence.

30:13.560 --> 30:15.122
That's biblical hospitality.

30:15.778 --> 30:34.196
She just so effortlessly seems to be safe to everyone she meets, absolutely everyone, that they all end up relaxing in her presence and laughing in her presence and then sharing something really vulnerable and deep that they never intended to share with anyone in her presence.

30:34.256 --> 30:35.157
How does she do that?

30:37.399 --> 30:39.301
She just sees people.

30:42.364 --> 30:44.786
She's not in a hurry, so you aren't either.

30:45.378 --> 30:48.382
And she's not trying to accomplish anything other than be with you.

30:48.422 --> 30:50.686
And so you relax in her presence.

30:50.726 --> 31:06.308
And she's genuinely curious about who you are and how you became that person to be seen by another, not looked at or looked through or looked past or used, but to be just seen by a loving, hospitable gaze.

31:06.368 --> 31:08.170
We all know what that feels like.

31:09.913 --> 31:11.315
And sadly, how rare it is.

31:12.877 --> 31:13.618
Kirsten just

31:13.826 --> 31:27.220
effortlessly draws people out by her presence because she offers people space to be seen, known, and healed in that order because hospitality always unfolds in that order.

31:28.261 --> 31:41.234
The poet and novelist Kave Akbar tells this beautiful story in one of his books about a middle-aged woman named Song who starts going to AA meetings in the church basement in New York City and her sponsor

31:41.378 --> 31:48.948
Jan had always taken her to this diner across the street for coffee and egg sandwiches after every meeting.

31:49.709 --> 32:05.810
And then there's this one day when she's three months sober that song has a horrible morning with her kids and then she gets a call home from school about the oldest who's acting up and she's irritated and stressed and eager to process all of it with

32:05.890 --> 32:13.097
Janet at the diner, but there's this ragged day one newcomer that Janet invites to come with them to lunch.

32:14.458 --> 32:17.681
And then Janet buys her coffee in a sandwich.

32:18.462 --> 32:21.865
And the newcomer's just going on and on about herself and her problems.

32:21.945 --> 32:28.251
And she's got this like maybe half true story about how she became a down on her luck addict.

32:28.291 --> 32:29.973
And Song keeps trying to get a word in.

32:30.373 --> 32:35.538
But this lady that they're probably never going to even see again is sucking all the out of the room.

32:35.650 --> 32:42.878
And then finally, she gets up to go to the bathroom and Janet looks across the table and says, Song, I need you to listen to me.

32:43.619 --> 32:46.162
You are not the patient today.

32:48.985 --> 33:00.178
Bill W, the co-founder of Alcoholics Anonymous, tells of this pivotal moment in his own sobriety journey when he had been working the steps and advancing in sobriety, but then the temptation to drink

33:00.450 --> 33:08.978
came on so strong that he tried everything he could to shake it and just couldn't until right on the verge of relapse.

33:08.998 --> 33:10.680
This crazy thought occurred to him.

33:12.522 --> 33:13.963
I need another alcoholic.

33:15.305 --> 33:18.948
And so he went to a meeting and he found someone to serve, and it was that.

33:18.988 --> 33:28.978
It was seeing and welcoming, but the stranger and the healer in his presence, the calmed Bill's nerves and restored his clarity.

33:29.410 --> 33:38.284
and the 12th of the 12th steps, which is all about hospitality to others, is a result of that encounter.

33:38.965 --> 33:54.130
The 12th step is the result of a man in recovery, an apprentice being redeemed, hitting the ceiling of his own formation by practice, and then allowing hospitality to a stranger, lead him where he did not want to go.

33:54.530 --> 33:57.354
Jesus to Peter on that walk on the beach.

33:57.454 --> 33:59.496
It's Bill W at the end of his robe.

33:59.597 --> 34:00.978
It's song at the diner.

34:01.319 --> 34:06.185
It's the Holy Spirit to every disciple who journeys long enough on the narrow way.

34:06.926 --> 34:08.608
You are not the patient today.

34:10.311 --> 34:11.572
Now this is really important.

34:12.614 --> 34:14.416
In AA, you never graduate.

34:15.077 --> 34:17.460
You never stop working the steps.

34:18.421 --> 34:22.066
You just climb through the steps and then you start back at step one.

34:25.090 --> 34:26.332
Bethany, I know what you're thinking.

34:26.653 --> 34:29.798
Brian McKnight, back at once, just flashed in my mind as well.

34:30.739 --> 34:34.625
Homecoming dance, 1999, last song, there she is across.

34:34.725 --> 34:36.809
Anyway, stay with me, guys, okay?

34:36.829 --> 34:38.231
Stay focused, don't go there.

34:39.894 --> 34:52.594
You never stop working the steps, but as you mature in your recovery, you start showing up to meetings with this motive and responsibility that, hey, I'm not the patient today.

34:53.890 --> 35:01.781
And your sobriety increasingly depends on freely giving all that you've freely received, hospitably away to others.

35:03.043 --> 35:10.494
At Bridgestown, we try to embody the treasures of the recovery community holistically in our church, but especially through the Bridgestown recovery community.

35:11.135 --> 35:17.664
And I just want to say to those of you in this congregation who are in recovery, what a gift you are to the rest of us.

35:19.086 --> 35:21.970
And what precious wisdom you have

35:22.370 --> 35:25.794
and what stunning hospitality you extend.

35:27.015 --> 35:35.985
According to our most recent data, 86% of this congregation has been following Jesus for 10 years or more.

35:37.627 --> 35:51.282
So to those of you in that category of whom I am one, and so I'm also speaking to myself here, I just want to lovingly, gently, but clearly say, never stop working the practices, and

35:51.490 --> 35:53.172
you are not the patient today.

35:55.034 --> 36:12.516
Your ongoing formation, probably more than you think, hinges on your willingness to show up to this room with that mindset, and as you do, to begin to show up to every other room you enter with that mindset.

36:13.617 --> 36:20.786
So there's generosity, hospitality, and then finally confession, which is the practice of consent with my image.

36:21.666 --> 36:29.867
In 2 Corinthians 12 Paul says something absolutely nonsensical to modern culture, but absolutely essential to kingdom culture.

36:31.391 --> 36:37.266
But Jesus said to me, my grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect and weakest.

36:37.378 --> 36:43.767
Therefore, I will boast all the more gladly about my weaknesses so that Christ's power may rest on me.

36:43.787 --> 36:54.323
That is why, for Christ's sake, I delight in weaknesses, in insults and hardships and persecutions and difficulties for when I am weak, then I am strong."

36:55.665 --> 37:07.122
Now, when I say the word confession, depending on your background, you likely picture either a booth with a priest or a gender-specific small group meeting where you are naming an ongoing struggle with sexual sobriety.

37:07.778 --> 37:10.383
And confession includes that, both of those.

37:11.204 --> 37:16.894
But I want to broaden that definition to boasting in my weakness.

37:17.715 --> 37:19.919
That's the sort of confession that I have in mind.

37:19.939 --> 37:26.090
And the variety that we are all in need of giving and receiving every time we gather.

37:27.052 --> 37:33.042
Community is the most universal longing in today's socially fragmented world of screens and personas.

37:33.698 --> 37:38.906
But we also struggle to create the through thick and thin community that we all want.

37:39.887 --> 37:52.445
I mean, we can even get together with a group of people who all believe in that sort of community, commit to being those sorts of people to each other and sometimes even taste it for a time, but we struggle to maintain it.

37:53.146 --> 37:59.015
Community, it seems, is very easy to dream and very hard to realize.

38:00.056 --> 38:01.138
Why is that?

38:01.826 --> 38:07.795
Because dreams are made of our collective strengths, but community is made of our collective weaknesses.

38:09.598 --> 38:18.633
Amos, my three-year-old, is objectively the most helpless member of my family, and he is the one who undoubtedly draws out the best in the rest of us.

38:19.995 --> 38:27.026
Hank cares for him and patiently serves him and carries him and reads to him and listens to him.

38:27.106 --> 38:33.314
Kirsten adores him and cherishes him and endures his toddler rants and demands with tenderness and mercy.

38:33.955 --> 38:36.879
I play with him and delight with him and laugh with him.

38:37.299 --> 38:42.766
No one makes me smile more frequently than Amos and no one makes me take myself less seriously than Amos.

38:43.607 --> 38:47.312
And Simon mostly fights with him, but we're believing for a miracle.

38:47.372 --> 38:49.795
We're holding out for a miracle there.

38:51.858 --> 38:55.122
Weakness, his personal

38:55.298 --> 38:56.962
unfiltered weakness.

38:57.283 --> 39:01.033
That's the magic that Amos uses to draw at the very best in the rest of us.

39:01.615 --> 39:02.176
Weakness.

39:03.018 --> 39:06.608
That's the magic that makes for the most tight-knit, loving communities.

39:07.571 --> 39:10.418
Western culture is built on an efficiency mentality.

39:10.914 --> 39:16.582
Your business, your office, your social media profile, your social circle, to some degree or another.

39:17.003 --> 39:20.367
People are valuable or expendable based on their utility.

39:20.808 --> 39:23.472
The strength that they bring to the efficiency machine.

39:23.933 --> 39:27.718
Church, on the other hand, is built on a love mentality.

39:28.419 --> 39:33.426
And if it's love that we're after, then the weak are the most valuable.

39:34.178 --> 39:41.107
Because like little Amos in my family, they have the power to draw out the very best in the rest of us.

39:42.028 --> 39:47.975
The weakest are the most essential least expendable members of a community that is built on love.

39:49.057 --> 39:55.985
My grace is sufficient for you, said Jesus, for my power is made perfect in weakness.

39:56.586 --> 39:59.009
This leads us to a very important question.

39:59.690 --> 40:02.994
Am I willing to sometimes be the weak one?

40:05.634 --> 40:10.860
the one who is broken, helpless in need.

40:12.302 --> 40:28.882
Will I allow community to be built around my weakness and God's power, or will I demand a more shallow kind of community that maintains the illusion of my strength and also pushes out God's power?

40:30.274 --> 40:40.086
So this week, as we gather together in our Bridgion communities around the table, we're gonna continue the practice of community through the daily prayer of examine.

40:40.687 --> 40:45.633
We're gonna take an abbreviated approach to this ancient prayer, but hey, you gotta start somewhere.

40:46.213 --> 40:56.466
So for the week ahead, we're gonna simplify the examine down to just three steps, three movements of prayer to be observed in community and then practice individually each day

40:56.578 --> 40:59.141
each following day in the evening.

40:59.541 --> 41:01.203
Those movements are gratitude.

41:01.864 --> 41:06.329
So start by thanking God for every big and small gift you can possibly recount from your day.

41:06.870 --> 41:07.630
Then review.

41:08.311 --> 41:21.586
Go back through the day noting the whispers of the spirit you missed and those you responded to particularly pay attention for who you saw and welcomed hospitably and those you might have looked past.

41:21.826 --> 41:36.607
And then third, confess, name any and every way you fell short today, receiving the forgiveness that he freely gives, a forgiveness that is mysteriously but certainly even more powerful to shape and redeem you than perfection.

41:37.147 --> 41:39.431
So how is that supposed to counterform me?

41:40.112 --> 41:43.917
How is that supposed to strengthen me to swim against the current of control?

41:44.578 --> 41:47.602
Because generosity is the overflow of gratitude.

41:48.418 --> 41:58.770
It is very hard to not feel rich when I am savoring the abundance I have rather than focusing on what I lack.

41:59.426 --> 42:08.820
And because hospitality begins with seeing, and as I practice recognizing God braided through my day in hindsight, I become more attentive to God in the present moment.

42:08.840 --> 42:14.628
And lastly, because bringing my weakness to community is the overflow of bringing my confession to God.

42:15.029 --> 42:20.997
When I learn the power of bringing my weakness to God, I gain the strength and conviction to show the same to others.

42:21.378 --> 42:26.866
Generosity is the overflow of gratitude, hospitality,

42:26.914 --> 42:33.620
is the overflow of reviewing my day with God and weakness is the overflow of confession.

42:34.541 --> 42:39.726
Be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect.

42:40.627 --> 42:43.610
Jesus calls us to perfection, but Jesus is not a perfectionist.

42:44.571 --> 42:48.635
Jesus calls us to perfection, but Jesus does not call us to become perfectionist.

42:48.995 --> 42:51.317
How then do we arrive where Jesus calls us?

42:55.381 --> 42:56.402
Daddy, it's okay.

42:57.826 --> 43:03.086
Just try to do a little bit better next time and be a little bit more like Jesus by bedtime.

43:05.736 --> 43:06.258
That's how.

43:07.842 --> 43:09.885
Spiritual formation is not a quick fix.

43:09.945 --> 43:16.033
It's not a self-deprecating war against your humanity or a personal training program to get the results you want.

43:16.333 --> 43:20.899
It's not code language for narcissistic wellness just cloaked in the veil of spirituality.

43:21.260 --> 43:22.822
It is the decision and aim.

43:23.182 --> 43:30.732
I'm gonna order my life in such a way to try to look a little bit more like Jesus by the time I lay my head on the pillow tonight.

43:31.153 --> 43:35.218
Because if I do that for a year or a couple of years,

43:35.714 --> 43:38.077
or a decade or maybe even for decades.

43:38.618 --> 43:39.459
You know what happens?

43:40.480 --> 43:47.069
I slowly, subtly grow into a person who looks a whole lot more like Jesus.

43:47.750 --> 43:52.896
Let's stand and respond together.

43:52.916 --> 43:56.781
Thanks for joining the Bridgestown family as we engage in this teaching series.

43:57.482 --> 44:03.570
To learn more about the life of our church and how you can get involved, visit bridgestown.church.com.

44:04.066 --> 44:12.262
If you're interested in contributing financially to Bridgestown Church and to our ministry, you can do that at bridgestown.church.gov.

44:13.004 --> 44:22.322
Wherever you're joining us from, we hope this resource blesses you and encourages you to be with Jesus, become like Jesus, and do what Jesus did.

